Exploratory Analysis¶

  1. What are busiest locations and hours?
  2. How are passengers per trip, payment type, fare and tip amounts distributed?
  3. How do times and fares vary by trips?
  4. Is it possible to characterise taxi drivers based on work hours and how much they make? # Open Questions
  5. What features influence fare and tip amounts?
  6. Can we build a model to predict fare and tip amount?
  7. If you were a taxi owner, how would you maximize your earnings in a day?

The data: NYC taxi data January 2013¶

Describe the Variables

  • medallion : from wikipedia: A taxi medallion, also known as a CPNC (Certificate of Public Necessity and Convenience), is a transferable permit...cities in the US use these in their taxi licensing systems
  • hack licence : To operate a vehicle as a yellow cab, you must complete the TLC hack-up certification and inspection. (nyc1.gov)
  • vendor_id : the LPEP provider
  • rate_code :
  • store_and_fwd_flag : indicates if the driver had no internet at the time and hada to forward the data later (flag indicates penalty for this)
  • pickup and drop off
  • passenger count
  • trip_time_in_secs
  • trip_distance in km
  • MTA tax is .50 imposed by NYC paid by passenger (dropping from future analysis) MTA Tax. The MTA Tax is the 50-cent tax on taxicab trips that is imposed by article 29-A of the New York State Tax Law.
  • Vendor ID - code indicating the TPEP provider - dropping

Introduction

The urls for the data sets were given as: https://archive.org/download/nycTaxiTripData2013/trip_data.7z https://archive.org/download/nycTaxiTripData2013/trip_fare.7z

Trip and fare data were obtained by visiting the location where the .7z files are hosted: https://archive.org/download/nycTaxiTripData2013

The individual data files for each month were available for download at this location.

def get_date_time_formats(df):
    df['pickup_datetime'] = [pd.Timestamp(d) for d in df['pickup_datetime']]
    df['p_date'] = [d.date() for d in df['pickup_datetime']]
    df['p_day_name'] = [d.day_name() for d in df['pickup_datetime']]
    df['p_hour'] = [d.hour for d in df['pickup_datetime']]

def get_neighborhoods(df):
    coords1_df= list(zip(df['pickup_latitude'],df['pickup_longitude']))
    df['p_nhood'] = [d['name'] for d in rg.search(coords1_df)]
    coords2_df = list(zip(df['dropoff_latitude'], df['dropoff_longitude']))
    df['d_nhood'] =[d['name'] for d in rg.search(coords2_df)]

def plot_elbow_graph(dataset, k_range=range(1, 11)): 

    # A list holds the inertia values for each k 

    inertia_lst = [] 

    for k in k_range: 

        km_model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1) 

        km_model.fit(dataset) 

        inertia_lst.append(km_model.inertia_) 

    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6)) 

    plt.plot(k_range, inertia_lst) 

    plt.xticks(k_range) 

    plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters") 

    plt.ylabel("Inertia") 

    plt.show()
    
def plot_silhouette_graph(dataset, k_range=range(2, 11)): 

    # A list holds the silhouette coefficients for each k 

    silhouette_coefficients = [] 

    for k in k_range: 

        km_model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1) 

        km_model.fit(dataset) 

        score = silhouette_score(dataset, km_model.labels_) 

        silhouette_coefficients.append(score) 

    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6)) 

    plt.plot(k_range, silhouette_coefficients) 

    plt.xticks(k_range) 

    plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters") 

    plt.ylabel("Silhouette Coefficient") 

    plt.show()
